 age of Napoleon. “A remarkable book that wonderfully vivifies an understudied era in the history of Rome. . . . This book will engage anyone interested in early modern cities, the relationship between religion and daily life, and the history of the city of Rome.”—Journal of Modern History “An engaging account of Tosca’s Rome. . . . Nicassio provides a fluent introduction to her subject.”—History Today “Meticulously researched, drawing on a host of original manuscripts, memoirs, personal letters, and secondary sources, enabling [Nicassio] to bring her story to life.”—History  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226579740423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226579740.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles